=== phpunit/core rules ===

## PHPUnit Core

- This application uses PHPUnit for testing. All tests must be written as PHPUnit classes. Use `php artisan make:test --phpunit <name>` to create a new test.
- If you see a test using "Pest", convert it to PHPUnit.
- Every time a test has been updated, run that singular test.
- When the tests relating to your feature are passing, ask the user if they would like to also run the entire test suite to make sure everything is still passing.
- Tests should test all of the happy paths, failure paths, and weird paths.
- You must not remove any tests or test files from the tests directory without approval. These are not temporary or helper files, these are core to the application.

### Running Tests
- Run the minimal number of tests, using an appropriate filter, before finalizing.
- To run all tests: `php artisan test`.
- To run all tests in a file: `php artisan test tests/Feature/ExampleTest.php`.
- To filter on a particular test name: `php artisan test --filter=testName` (recommended after making a change to a related file).


=== security rules ===

## Security Best Practices

### Input Validation and Sanitization
- Always validate and sanitize user input using Form Requests.
- Use Laravel's validation rules for data integrity.
- Sanitize file uploads and user-generated content.
- Never trust user input, even from authenticated users.

### Authentication and Authorization
- Use Laravel Sanctum for API authentication when needed.
- Implement proper authorization with Policies.
- Use middleware for route protection.
- Implement rate limiting for sensitive endpoints.

### CSRF and XSS Protection
- Include `@csrf` in all forms.
- Use `{{ }}` for escaping output (enabled by default).
- Use `{!! !!}` only for trusted content.
- Never output unescaped user input.

### Mass Assignment Protection
- Always use `$fillable` or `$guarded` on models.
- Never use `$guarded = []` in production code.
- Validate and filter input before mass assignment.

### SQL Injection Prevention
- Use Eloquent ORM (automatically uses parameterized queries).
- Avoid raw queries unless absolutely necessary.
- If using raw queries, always use parameter bindings.

### Secure Headers
- Enforce HTTPS in production.
- Set secure cookie flags.
- Use security headers middleware when available.
- Implement HSTS for HTTPS enforcement.

### File Upload Security
- Validate file types and sizes.
- Store uploaded files outside the web root when possible.
- Scan uploaded files for malware if handling user uploads.
- Use safe file naming to prevent directory traversal.

### Configuration Security
- Never commit `.env` files to version control.
- Use environment variables for sensitive data.
- Use Laravel's encryption for sensitive stored data.
- Keep dependencies updated for security patches.


=== performance rules ===

## Performance Optimization

### Database Optimization
- Use eager loading (`with()`) to prevent N+1 queries.
- Add appropriate database indexes on frequently queried columns.
- Use `select()` to fetch only needed columns.
- Implement database query result caching for expensive queries.
- Use `chunk()` for processing large datasets.

### Query Optimization Examples
```php
// ❌ N+1 Query Problem - Avoid this
$games = Game::all();
foreach ($games as $game) {
    $players = $game->players; // N additional queries
}

// ✅ Eager Loading - Use this instead
$games = Game::with('players')->get();

// ✅ Selective Column Loading
$games = Game::select(['id', 'name', 'status'])
    ->with(['players' => function ($query) {
        $query->select(['id', 'game_id', 'name']);
    }])
    ->get();
```

### Caching Strategies
- Use Redis or Memcached for application-level caching.
- Cache expensive database queries with `Cache::remember()`.
- Cache configuration and routes in production.
- Implement cache tags for selective invalidation when needed.

### Application Performance
- Cache configuration and routes in production: `php artisan config:cache` and `php artisan route:cache`.
- Use API Resources for consistent JSON responses.
- Implement pagination for large datasets.
- Use cursor pagination for "infinite scroll" interfaces.

### Code Performance
- Avoid unnecessary loops and nested iterations.
- Use efficient data structures (e.g., Collections).
- Minimize bundle sizes and use lazy loading for frontend assets.
- Profile performance hotspots before optimizing.


=== architecture rules ===

## Architecture and Code Organization

### Separation of Concerns
- **Controllers**: Handle HTTP requests and responses only. Delegate business logic to services.
- **Services**: Business logic, data access, and validation.
- **Models**: Database relationships, accessors/mutators, and scopes.
- **Views**: Presentation logic only. No business logic.

### File Size Guidelines
- **Controllers**: Keep under 100 lines per method, prefer thin controllers.
- **Service Classes**: Keep under 300 lines, single responsibility principle.
- **Blade Views**: Keep under 200 lines. Break into components when needed.
- **JavaScript Files**: Keep classes under 400 lines. Split when complexity grows.

### Service Layer Pattern
- Use service classes for complex business logic.
- Services should have single responsibility.
- Services return consistent result arrays: `['success' => bool, 'data' => array, 'error' => string]`.
- Use dependency injection for service dependencies.

### Repository Pattern
- Consider repository pattern for complex data access.
- Use Eloquent models and relationships before repositories.
- Only use repositories when data access logic is complex or needs abstraction.

### Code Organization
- Follow existing directory structure.
- Group related functionality together.
- Use meaningful file and directory names.
- Keep related files in the same namespace/directory.

### Component Reusability
- Check for existing components before creating new ones.
- Extract reusable logic into services or helpers.
- Use Blade components for reusable view elements.
- Follow DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle.

### Error Handling
- Use try-catch blocks for error-prone operations.
- Return consistent error responses.
- Log errors appropriately (avoid logging sensitive data).
- Use Laravel's exception handling system.


=== testing/tdd rules ===

## Testing and TDD Best Practices

### Test-Driven Development (TDD)
- Write failing tests before implementing features when practical.
- Use tests to drive implementation and ensure quality.
- Refactor code after tests pass.
- Maintain test coverage for critical functionality.

### Test Structure
- Use descriptive test method names that explain what is being tested.
- Test one concept per test method.
- Arrange-Act-Assert pattern for test organization.
- Use factories for test data generation.

### Test Categories
- **Unit Tests**: Test individual methods and functions in isolation.
- **Feature Tests**: Test complete workflows and user interactions.
- **Integration Tests**: Test component interactions when needed.

### Test Data Management
- Use factories for creating test models.
- Use database transactions for test isolation when appropriate.
- Clean up test data properly.
- Use realistic test data scenarios.

### Test Coverage
- Focus on critical business logic and user-facing features.
- Test both success and failure scenarios.
- Test edge cases and boundary conditions.
- Don't aim for 100% coverage - focus on meaningful tests.

### Testing Best Practices
- Keep tests fast and focused.
- Use proper test isolation.
- Avoid testing implementation details.
- Test behavior, not implementation.
- Use meaningful assertions and error messages.


=== code quality rules ===

## Code Quality Standards

### Code Review Checklist
- [ ] Follows PSR-12 coding standards
- [ ] Proper type hints and return types
- [ ] Meaningful variable and method names
- [ ] Single responsibility principle
- [ ] Proper error handling
- [ ] Security considerations addressed
- [ ] Performance considerations addressed
- [ ] Tests written and passing
- [ ] Documentation added when needed

### PHPDoc Standards
- Document all public methods with PHPDoc.
- Include parameter and return type documentation.
- Document complex business logic.
- Use array shape definitions for complex arrays.

### Code Complexity
- Keep methods small and focused (prefer under 20-30 lines).
- Avoid deep nesting (max 3-4 levels).
- Extract complex logic into separate methods or services.
- Use early returns to reduce nesting.

### Naming Conventions
- Use descriptive names that explain intent.
- Use verb-noun pattern for methods: `calculateTotal()`, `validateInput()`.
- Use noun pattern for classes: `GameEngine`, `UserService`.
- Use camelCase for variables and methods.
- Use PascalCase for classes and namespaces.
